00:00:01.939 --> 00:00:06.880
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Good afternoon and welcome
to YouTube Headquarters in San Bruno, California,

00:00:06.880 --> 00:00:09.530
if you're joining us from somewhere on the
internet.

00:00:09.530 --> 00:00:14.370
Our guest today at YouTube is an actor who
has appeared in some of the comedies that

00:00:14.370 --> 00:00:15.949
defined the last decade.

00:00:15.949 --> 00:00:22.420
I'm talking about movies like 40-Year-Old
Virgin and Superbad, Forgetting Sarah Marshall,

00:00:22.420 --> 00:00:27.620
Get Him to the Greek, Funny People and more,
but he's here today to share with us some

00:00:27.620 --> 00:00:32.980
of his experiences working in a dramatic role
on a movie that opens this weekend.

00:00:32.980 --> 00:00:34.489
The movie is Moneyball.

00:00:34.489 --> 00:00:39.649
Please welcome me or please join me in welcoming
to YouTube, Jonah Hill.

00:00:39.649 --> 00:00:41.480
[applause]

00:00:41.480 --> 00:00:46.970
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: Hello.

00:00:46.970 --> 00:00:50.839
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: How're you doing?

00:00:50.839 --> 00:00:51.839
How're you doing?

00:00:51.839 --> 00:00:52.839
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: I'm well.

00:00:52.839 --> 00:00:53.839
How are you?

00:00:53.839 --> 00:00:54.839
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Good, good.

00:00:54.839 --> 00:00:58.420
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: Thanks for joining internet
if you're watching this.

00:00:58.420 --> 00:01:00.280
Haven't seen you in awhile.

00:01:00.280 --> 00:01:06.550
I hope your hair still looks as good as last
time I saw it, internet, and why'd you break

00:01:06.550 --> 00:01:07.550
up with me?

00:01:07.550 --> 00:01:08.550
That wasn't nice.

00:01:08.550 --> 00:01:09.550
OK.

00:01:09.550 --> 00:01:10.550
How are you guys doing?

00:01:10.550 --> 00:01:11.850
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Excellent.

00:01:11.850 --> 00:01:16.180
So Jonah, I, I could explain what, what Moneyball
is as a movie, but I'm sure people would rather

00:01:16.180 --> 00:01:18.970
hear you tell 'em about it.

00:01:18.970 --> 00:01:26.910
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: Moneyball is a drama about baseball,
but, you know, it's about the 2002 Oakland

00:01:26.910 --> 00:01:34.570
A's and Billy Beane and my character, Peter
Brand, using this technique called sabermetrics

00:01:34.570 --> 00:01:36.610
or moneyball as they call it.

00:01:36.610 --> 00:01:44.610
And they use this technique of a different
way of finding value in players to, to build

00:01:44.610 --> 00:01:49.350
a team with very little money that ends up
winning 20 straight games in a row, which

00:01:49.350 --> 00:01:50.990
breaks a lot of records.

00:01:50.990 --> 00:01:54.460
Now on paper this sounds like the most boring
movie ever made.

00:01:54.460 --> 00:01:55.460
[laughter]

00:01:55.460 --> 00:02:00.350
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: About, a movie about baseball
statistics.

00:02:00.350 --> 00:02:05.770
But Aaron Sorkin, who wrote The Social Network,
and Steve Zaillian, who wrote Schindler's

00:02:05.770 --> 00:02:07.120
List, wrote, wrote this movie.

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:12.819
And Aaron Sorkin, and I'm paraphrasing here,
said about it, just as how The Social Network

00:02:12.819 --> 00:02:17.310
on paper sounds very boring, you know a movie
about someone inventing a website, maybe not

00:02:17.310 --> 00:02:23.030
to the people in this room, [chuckles] [audience
laughs] but to me that sounded very boring.

00:02:23.030 --> 00:02:29.230
And, and, and you know you watch that film
and it's riveting and really groundbreaking

00:02:29.230 --> 00:02:33.040
and cool and a great drama, and it's the same
thing about Moneyball because the filmmakers

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:39.590
really use baseball as a really beautiful
aesthetic backdrop to tell a really moving

00:02:39.590 --> 00:02:41.980
story about underdogs and being undervalued.

00:02:41.980 --> 00:02:48.260
And that's the story I connected to and also
it stars Brad Pitt and myself and Philip Seymour

00:02:48.260 --> 00:02:54.190
Hoffman, so the three most handsome guys in
the world, obviously they, they found us all

00:02:54.190 --> 00:02:56.140
and paired us together finally.

00:02:56.140 --> 00:02:57.140
[laughter]

00:02:57.140 --> 00:03:01.459
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: And for me it's exciting because
it's you know you're used to seeing me in

00:03:01.459 --> 00:03:06.930
comedies and this is, you know I love comedy
movies and dramatic movies, and for me it's

00:03:06.930 --> 00:03:12.990
a really big opportunity to show you guys
what I could do in a dramatic role and I hope

00:03:12.990 --> 00:03:15.600
you like it, that'd be nice, yeah, sure.

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:16.600
[laughter]

00:03:16.600 --> 00:03:21.349
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Now it's not as if you only
done kind of one particular style of comedy

00:03:21.349 --> 00:03:26.730
over the years, I mean, The Invention of Lying
had a very kind of specific tone to it.

00:03:26.730 --> 00:03:31.850
And then even Funny People was a very kind
of naturalistic movie, but still this is a

00:03:31.850 --> 00:03:34.360
big step up for you, kind of being head to
head with Brad Pitt?

00:03:34.360 --> 00:03:37.720
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: Well, I made um, I made a movie
last year called Cyrus, which was a smaller

00:03:37.720 --> 00:03:40.240
movie that not a lot of people saw.

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:46.739
And it was myself and John C. Reilly and Marisa
Tomei, and that was kind of good, like it

00:03:46.739 --> 00:03:52.230
was a good bridge way in between some of the
comedies I made and, and, and dramatic work

00:03:52.230 --> 00:03:56.280
because it was funny and it was a drama, it
had both things in it.

00:03:56.280 --> 00:04:03.810
And yeah I mean the thing about the comedies
I've done is to me at the time when, when

00:04:03.810 --> 00:04:09.640
I had met Judd Apatow and all these guys you
know like and we all started working together,

00:04:09.640 --> 00:04:14.430
it did feel very punk rock and different than
what was going on in comedy.

00:04:14.430 --> 00:04:19.780
It felt like a different thing that was happening
and we all kind of have the same energy and,

00:04:19.780 --> 00:04:24.760
and, and take on what we wanted to do, led
by Judd obviously.

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:30.520
And you know but now it's years later and
those movies have been copied now to death

00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:36.650
and you know in my mind I'm always like, what's
next, how do I evolve and how do you evolve

00:04:36.650 --> 00:04:40.840
and then you watch the way that Judd is evolving
as a filmmaker and Seth Rogen and Evan Goldberger

00:04:40.840 --> 00:04:47.260
evolving as filmmakers, and now my evolution
involves doing movies like Cyrus and Moneyball

00:04:47.260 --> 00:04:52.480
and that's stuff I'm really psyched about,
you know, so hopefully I could get to do both

00:04:52.480 --> 00:04:54.800
of those things, the comedy and drama.

00:04:54.800 --> 00:04:58.930
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Now, I've, I've heard some
actors say that it's very intimidating to

00:04:58.930 --> 00:05:02.680
work opposite someone like Robert De Niro
because it's Robert De Niro and obviously

00:05:02.680 --> 00:05:06.910
Brad Pitt is just so damn handsome.

00:05:06.910 --> 00:05:09.730
Do you have to just like stay around for 20
minutes to see if it goes away?

00:05:09.730 --> 00:05:10.730
