00:05:10.730 --> 00:05:12.020
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: No, you know, honestly, like

00:05:12.020 --> 00:05:13.020
[laughter]

00:05:13.020 --> 00:05:14.020
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: To what?

00:05:14.020 --> 00:05:16.520
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: To just, you know, get past
the initial shock?

00:05:16.520 --> 00:05:18.200
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: This guy.

00:05:18.200 --> 00:05:19.200
[laughter]

00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:20.300
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: Calm down.

00:05:20.300 --> 00:05:22.960
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: I have more questions like
this, so.

00:05:22.960 --> 00:05:24.060
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: Yeah, yeah.

00:05:24.060 --> 00:05:28.729
It's the accent mixed with the tattoos mixed
with the stare mixed with the smile, it's,

00:05:28.729 --> 00:05:29.729
it's.

00:05:29.729 --> 00:05:30.729
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: We'll be fine.

00:05:30.729 --> 00:05:31.729
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: Alright.

00:05:31.729 --> 00:05:41.460
If anything happens to me, um, I'm in northern
California, in a really weird professor auditorium?

00:05:41.460 --> 00:05:42.460
[laughter]

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:46.570
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: I don't know where I am.

00:05:46.570 --> 00:05:53.900
But, no, I mean you know obviously I was intimidated
when I got this part because it was myself,

00:05:53.900 --> 00:05:57.870
you know I'm the second lead in this movie
with Brad Pitt and Philip Seymour Hoffman's

00:05:57.870 --> 00:06:03.241
in the movie and you know Bennett Miller's
directing it who directed Capote, and Aaron

00:06:03.241 --> 00:06:07.550
Sorkin wrote Social Network, and Steve Zaillian,
who wrote Schindler's List, and it just is

00:06:07.550 --> 00:06:13.730
this really surreal dream-like experience
from day one and so you know the first day

00:06:13.730 --> 00:06:18.750
of rehearsals I was really nervous, but I
was like, I can either be really freaked out

00:06:18.750 --> 00:06:24.180
or I can kick my nerves to the curb for a
second and try and deliver for these people

00:06:24.180 --> 00:06:28.190
who took a chance on giving me an opportunity
to do something truly different, so.

00:06:28.190 --> 00:06:31.410
I just wanted to come through for them and
if I was sitting around being nervous about

00:06:31.410 --> 00:06:36.730
how talented everyone was, I probably would
of just thought about that as opposed to doing

00:06:36.730 --> 00:06:38.000
a good job.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:39.270
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Sure.

00:06:39.270 --> 00:06:43.040
Now obviously Moneyball really is a, it's
a number of things.

00:06:43.040 --> 00:06:47.580
It's a human interest story, it's the story
of Billy Beane, but I don't want to underplay

00:06:47.580 --> 00:06:51.090
the role of statistics, obviously we probably
have some you know programmers and engineers.

00:06:51.090 --> 00:06:52.341
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: Well you guys are nerds, so
it's like

00:06:52.341 --> 00:06:53.341
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Yes, exactly.

00:06:53.341 --> 00:06:54.380
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: really exciting for you.

00:06:54.380 --> 00:06:56.090
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: There are some people here
I'm sure

00:06:56.090 --> 00:06:58.360
[laughter]
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: Wrong crowd, wrong room, wrong

00:06:58.360 --> 00:06:59.360
room.

00:06:59.360 --> 00:07:02.330
The internet liked that more than this room.

00:07:02.330 --> 00:07:03.360
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: They don't like being called
nerds.

00:07:03.360 --> 00:07:05.800
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: I'm leaving, no.

00:07:05.800 --> 00:07:10.940
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: But I mean how did you deal
with, did you method act your way through

00:07:10.940 --> 00:07:12.600
the, the statistical stuff?

00:07:12.600 --> 00:07:18.440
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: No, well, honestly, I, you know,
I realized I had never played a character

00:07:18.440 --> 00:07:21.389
with a skill before, of any kind.

00:07:21.389 --> 00:07:22.389
[laughter]

00:07:22.389 --> 00:07:28.699
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: And now the character I was
playing had to be a brilliant statistician

00:07:28.699 --> 00:07:33.990
and mathematician, so I had a statistics tutor
and a mathematics tutor and I think that was

00:07:33.990 --> 00:07:39.790
probably the hardest job on Moneyball was
teaching me how to count past 10 probably,

00:07:39.790 --> 00:07:44.310
because I'm very poor at math and science,
I was always really good at history and English

00:07:44.310 --> 00:07:46.500
and acting and stuff like that in school.

00:07:46.500 --> 00:07:49.690
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Now I did read somewhere that
apparently you were kind of suggest, it was

00:07:49.690 --> 00:07:54.039
suggested that you should deal with statistics
the same way that you, you kind of talk about

00:07:54.039 --> 00:07:56.780
other actors in Hollywood and their strengths
and weaknesses, so.

00:07:56.780 --> 00:07:58.200
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: Or filmmakers or.

00:07:58.200 --> 00:07:59.200
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: Sure.

00:07:59.200 --> 00:08:00.200
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: Yeah, movies themselves.

00:08:00.200 --> 00:08:02.389
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: So I was kind of wondering,
could you maybe give us an example and maybe

00:08:02.389 --> 00:08:05.520
give us like two of Seth Rogen's strengths
and one weakness.

00:08:05.520 --> 00:08:09.440
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: [laughing] I'm not gonna do
that.

00:08:09.440 --> 00:08:10.440
[laughter]

00:08:10.440 --> 00:08:11.440
&gt;&gt;Interviewer: He'll never know.

00:08:11.440 --> 00:08:13.389
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: Why would I want to?

