&gt;&gt;Interviewer: obviously Billy, as I say Billy
is a real character, you're playing more of

00:09:14.430 --> 00:09:19.440
a composite character maybe and it's a bigger
part perhaps than it is in the book.

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:24.130
Because in the book you know the character
of the statistician isn't drawn out as much

00:09:24.130 --> 00:09:28.700
and I maybe thought that would have been an
interesting opportunity to have that a little

00:09:28.700 --> 00:09:32.050
bit grounded in reality, but then you get
Aaron Sorkin writing out the role?

00:09:32.050 --> 00:09:36.560
&gt;&gt;Jonah Hill: Well I think, you know, my character
in this movie is a guy who would blend into

00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:38.240
a wall, right?

00:09:38.240 --> 00:09:40.790
So he's never had a light shined on him before.

00:09:40.790 --> 00:09:43.270
He's never had someone empower him in any
way.

00:09:43.270 --> 00:09:50.120
He's someone who is doing the busy work on
a computer, no offense, [audience chuckles]

00:09:50.120 --> 00:09:55.160
and you don't usually see that person's story
is what I'm saying so for me I found it really

00:09:55.160 --> 00:09:58.961
unique to get to play a character where you're
getting to play someone who you're, you're

00:09:58.961 --> 00:10:01.060
hearing their story who you don't usually
get to see.

00:10:01.060 --> 00:10:06.060
And a guy like Billy, like Brad Pitt's character,
is the guy's character who you always see

00:10:06.060 --> 00:10:11.080
in a movie, the main protagonist, but the
cool thing is Brad's character was overvalued.

00:10:11.080 --> 00:10:16.100
He was told he was gonna be this big sports
star because he was handsome and he was good

00:10:16.100 --> 00:10:21.180
at baseball and he turned down going to Stanford
and he turned down getting an education and

00:10:21.180 --> 00:10:24.920
he fizzled out and he didn't become this big
sports star.

00:10:24.920 --> 00:10:27.149
And my character is undervalued.

00:10:27.149 --> 00:10:30.950
He's taken at face value, taken as a guy who
can just do busy work on a computer, but he

00:10:30.950 --> 00:10:35.779
has these really brilliant radical ideas and
Billy's the first person, Brad's character,

00:10:35.779 --> 00:10:41.019
Billy, is the first person who sees him and
goes, you're, you're, you're something special,

00:10:41.019 --> 00:10:42.800
you have something special to offer.

00:10:42.800 --> 00:10:44.490
And it's really cool to see that guy's story.

00:10:44.490 --> 00:10:46.060
So that's what I found really interesting.

00:10:46.060 --> 00:10:50.530
And it's kind of like seeing a baby use his
legs for the first time, you know, because

00:10:50.530 --> 00:10:55.630
he's never been empowered before, so he's
metaphorically wobbling around, you know,

00:10:55.630 --> 00:11:02.710
trying to learn how to walk, or trying to
learn how to deal with some sort of power,

00:11:02.710 --> 00:11:03.710
and that's exciting.

00:11:03.710 --> 00:11:04.710
Yeah.

